te Council issued to newsmen on Thursday in Sokoto.  The statement reads: “In view of the current situation caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, the Sultan hereby advises all District Heads and Imams in Sokoto State, to observe Eid prayers at their Juma’at Mosques. READ ALSO:INDUSTRILISATION: Minister of Mines and Steel to commission Shanghai Engineering Works in Imo  “This, in their respective towns and villages and not at Eid Grounds. Also the Muslim Communities throughout the country to do same to help curb the spread of COVID-19 pandemic in the country.  ” The Sultan declared Friday, July 31, as the 10th day of Dhul-Hijja 1441 AH and the day of Eid-el-Kabir for the year” statement said.  He felicitates with the Nigeria Muslim Ummah and wishes them Allah’s guidance and blessings.  Abubakar urged Muslim to continue to pray for peace, progress and development of the country, while wishing them happy Eid-el-Kabir. Vanguard The Sultan of Sokoto and Chairman Nigerian Supreme Council for Islamic Affairs, Alhaji Sa’ad Abubakar, has declared Sept. 1, 2017 as Eid-el-Kabir  day. August 23, 2017 In "News" The Sultan of Sokoto and Chairman, Nigerian Supreme Council for Islamic Affairs, Sa’ad Abubakar, has announced September 1, 2017 as Eid-el-Kabir day. The day had earlier been declared by the Saudi Arabian government as the day of the festival celebrated by Muslims all over the world. August 23, 2017 In "News" PRESIDENT Muhammadu Buhari has canceled this year's Sallah homage to him by the Muslim faithful at the Presidential Villa, Abuja. May 22, 2020 In "News"